Late, like I always am. Even though I pretend I'm a punctual person (Virgo illusion mode ON).
Late on the coming out day but not on my coming out: I basically never had to actually come out with people, especially with my family. 
My mom taught me how to be myself and how to be proud of who I am, so there was no need to tell her anything (and of course she knew it since day 0 already), same for my sister.
I always acted spontaneously and I was discovering myself, my sexuality, my identity, my body, and my emotions in a very open and youthful way and most of my friends knew I was gay before I did.

I officially came out to my "friends" when I was 14, but it was more like being left out.
We were a very close-knit group, never  apart from each other for more than 2 days. Eating, sleeping, skating (yes, I tried LOL), going on vacation, playing (yes, I mean masturbating), always together like brothers.
Suddenly, they all disappeared.
No reasons, no explanations, nothing.
It was such a shocking experience that I started shutting myself off. I became very introverted and insecure, I didn't want to go out or make new friends or anything.
I guess I was depressed and I never felt so alone.

I didn't know how to get out of that dark spiral and I thought I was going to be alone for the rest of my life. And my family didn't know how to help me out. 
That lasted 2 years, during which I got beaten and bullied at school. When I tried to react I just made worse and bigger "enemies".
My teachers saw everything without saying a word.

I often find myself thinking about that time of my life and how far I am now from that and how hard I worked to never let that happen again.
Coming out is important but being a good friend is fundamental and the process of self-discovery is so awful when you're a teenager it could leave you helpless and alone. Be there for others who are weak and fragile. 
Keep coming out and help other people doing it with compassion, love and understanding.
Give them the time they need and don't put pressure on their process.
Be grateful every day for being able to come out in your environment, many people can't because of homophobia, violence, religions or laws.
